    void llist::deleteFront(el_t&amp; OldNum) {	
    	if (isEmpty()) {
	    	throw underflow()
    	}

In case the list is empty we throw an exception (it will notify the developer that the calling code wrongly invoked `deleteFront()` on an already empty list);

	    else if (Count == 1) {              

In the case there is one node we do the following:

		    OldNum = Front-&gt;Elem;           
		
We return an element from the just being deleted node to the caller, since `Oldnum` parameter is a reference (`&amp;`) we can store the element at this reference and the caller will have access to it after the function ends;
		
		    Node *Second; // &lt;- this is useless!!

Declaration of a pointer for new node but it&#39;s not used so this line effectively does nothing (you can remove it);

		    delete Front;
		    Front = NULL; //missing!!
		
We delete the only existing `Front` node and memory occupied by it (along with `elem` field and all other if any) is freed;
note that you must add `Front = NULL;` to properly invalidate the `Front` pointer which now points to nothing;
		
		    Count--;
	    }
	
We decrement `Count` by `1` (to `0`) and finish.
	
	    else {
	
In the last case when more than 1 nodes exist:
	
		    OldNum = Front-&gt;Elem;
		
We return the element exactly as in above case;
		
		    Node *Second;
		    Second = Front-&gt;Next;
		
This one we need to temporarily &#39;remember&#39; the next node at the name `Second` (which will be the first one from now);
		
		    delete Front;
		
Now we delete the `First` node, its memory is freed;		

		    Front = Second;
		
Since `Front` pointer must always point to the first node we re-assign it with the `Second`	(this is why we remembered it);

		    Count--;
	    }

We decrement `Count` by `1` and finish;
However as Igor noted it all can be reduced to:

    if (isEmpty()) {
        throw underflow()
    }
    else {
        OldNum = Front-&gt;Elem;
        Node *Second;
        Second = Front-&gt;Next;
        delete Front;
        Front = Second;
        Count--;
    }

The `else` case will handle also the case with one node. Just the `NULL` value will be transferred from `Front-&gt;Next` to the `Front` pointer.

